00:13:54,113 --> 00:13:55,773
And I'm blocked.

324
00:13:55,853 --> 00:13:56,954
That's a fact.

325
00:13:57,434 --> 00:14:00,956
And it's about a project, and probably about a process, too.

326
00:14:02,910 --> 00:14:04,794
And we found, like, yeah, this seems to cover things.

327
00:14:04,894 --> 00:14:05,856
So that's kind of cool.

328
00:14:05,896 --> 00:14:06,858
That's kind of interesting.

329
00:14:08,100 --> 00:14:10,625
OK, well, so that's a way to break down information.

330
00:14:10,925 --> 00:14:13,951
Now we need to look at, like, where does that information go?

331
00:14:13,971 --> 00:14:15,274
Because information is not static.

332
00:14:16,340 --> 00:14:20,001
The first thing to think about is the fact that we ourselves are information networks.

333
00:14:20,782 --> 00:14:22,842
We are not just like a point on a graph.

334
00:14:23,122 --> 00:14:26,984
We are a complex information network inside ourselves and inside our minds.

335
00:14:27,444 --> 00:14:30,485
And if you've ever tried to think of a name and you can't think of it, and then two minutes

336
00:14:30,505 --> 00:14:34,467
later you thought of it, like, yeah, that's because the information was in there the whole

337
00:14:34,507 --> 00:14:34,807
time.

338
00:14:35,167 --> 00:14:36,548
It just had a little trouble.

339
00:14:36,848 --> 00:14:39,289
It got caught in a router somewhere and could not find its way.

340
00:14:40,449 --> 00:14:42,130
So first, we are information networks.

341
00:14:42,430 --> 00:14:44,111
But then, of course, it's hierarchical

342
00:14:44,171 --> 00:14:46,432
because you connect up with other people in the studio.

343
00:14:46,492 --> 00:14:48,173
So there's internal information flow

344
00:14:48,273 --> 00:14:49,773
and then there's external information flow.

345
00:14:50,253 --> 00:14:51,794
And then it's hierarchical again

346
00:14:52,714 --> 00:14:54,855
because the studio communicates with other entities.

347
00:14:55,215 --> 00:14:56,856
Maybe a publisher, maybe with your players,

348
00:14:56,876 --> 00:14:58,857
maybe you've got a licensor or the press

349
00:14:59,037 --> 00:15:00,838
or outsource partners or all kinds of other things.

350
00:15:00,878 --> 00:15:03,519
So you have these sort of hierarchies of information flow.

351
00:15:04,039 --> 00:15:05,399
All right, so that's useful to think about.

352
00:15:06,391 --> 00:15:09,834
But now, the way all information flows is not created equal.

353
00:15:12,015 --> 00:15:14,437
In the business world, we tend to use four main ways

354
00:15:15,097 --> 00:15:16,218
of communication.

355
00:15:17,339 --> 00:15:18,560
Face-to-face, we do a lot.

356
00:15:19,120 --> 00:15:21,162
More and more, we're doing Skype, sort of video conference,

357
00:15:21,942 --> 00:15:24,384
phone calls sometimes, and then lots and lots of email.

358
00:15:26,106 --> 00:15:28,647
And as much as some people like to believe that all these are

359
00:15:28,687 --> 00:15:30,529
equivalent, they certainly are not.

360
00:15:30,569 --> 00:15:32,710
We have lots of evidence that they are not.

361
00:15:32,770 --> 00:15:34,932
And it's interesting to wonder about why.

362
00:15:35,321 --> 00:15:39,625
The key seems to be that the things at the top you're getting much more

363
00:15:39,725 --> 00:15:42,888
information and the things at the bottom you're getting much less.

364
00:15:43,208 --> 00:15:48,453
Face to face communication is a lot of information because yes, you are

365
00:15:48,473 --> 00:15:51,856
hearing my words, but you're also hearing my tone of voice.

366
00:15:52,156 --> 00:15:56,160
You're seeing my facial expression, but then it gets even weirder and deeper

367
00:15:56,220 --> 00:15:59,643
than that because that's all with your conscious mind.

368
00:15:59,966 --> 00:16:03,569
Your subconscious mind is very good at communicating with other people face to face.

369
00:16:04,450 --> 00:16:07,412
There's well documented notion of micro expressions.

370
00:16:07,953 --> 00:16:12,036
Micro expressions are generally when there's a conflict within you, you want to communicate

371
00:16:12,116 --> 00:16:14,218
one thing but you want to hide your emotions.

372
00:16:14,539 --> 00:16:15,820
You can't hide them perfectly.

373
00:16:16,120 --> 00:16:17,181
And so there is a period.

374
00:16:17,601 --> 00:16:22,804
of about 40 milliseconds where you make these tiny expressions that show your true emotions.

375
00:16:23,724 --> 00:16:28,927
And you can't see them very well consciously, but your subconscious totally picks up on them.

376
00:16:29,347 --> 00:16:32,189
You ever have that moment someone's saying something you're like something's not right

377
00:16:32,249 --> 00:16:36,771
about that, that guy's trying to pull something. It's often because your subconscious picked up

378
00:16:36,831 --> 00:16:37,792
on a micro expression.

379
00:16:38,232 --> 00:16:40,615
Now, given that those last about 40 milliseconds,

380
00:16:41,035 --> 00:16:43,618
and given that Skype, on average,

381
00:16:43,698 --> 00:16:45,460
gives you about 20 frames a second,

382
00:16:45,980 --> 00:16:49,224
you are unlikely to pick up microexpressions through Skype.

383
00:16:50,425 --> 00:16:52,508
Um, so that's important.

384
00:16:53,429 --> 00:16:55,571
Uh, another one is, this is gonna sound really crazy,

385
00:16:55,911 --> 00:16:56,232
smell.

386
00:16:58,037 --> 00:17:04,541
we, a subconscious picks up on the smells of other people and emotions are communicated through smell.

387
00:17:05,122 --> 00:17:09,705
There have been studies done, it's a weird study, right? We have two groups, one group's going to watch a comedy movie,

388
00:17:09,965 --> 00:17:13,528
the other group's going to watch a horror movie, and they each put pads under their armpits,

389
00:17:14,209 --> 00:17:19,532
alright, and they watch the movie, and then the pads are collected up, and an unfortunate third group of people

390
00:17:21,694 --> 00:17:23,375
is asked to smell the pads.

391
00:17:24,759 --> 00:17:28,142
And better than average, they can tell which movie was being watched.

392
00:17:29,103 --> 00:17:33,667
Because you really can smell fear.

393
00:17:33,867 --> 00:17:35,269
But you can't smell it over Skype.

394
00:17:36,630 --> 00:17:36,910
Yet.

395
00:17:38,052 --> 00:17:39,033
No, I don't know what that means.

396
00:17:39,373 --> 00:17:45,299
Anyway, this is important because fear is an important thing on projects.

397
00:17:45,559 --> 00:17:47,441
You know, hey, are you going to get that done by Friday?

398
00:17:47,741 --> 00:17:49,443
Oh, yeah, yeah, I'm going to get it done, right?

399
00:17:49,767 --> 00:17:50,267
Yeah, really?

400
00:17:50,428 --> 00:17:50,628
Right?

401
00:17:51,108 --> 00:17:54,730
And anyway, so face-to-face is really, really important.

402
00:17:55,510 --> 00:17:56,731
Tone of voice is really important,

403
00:17:56,751 --> 00:18:00,312
which is why even a phone call can be better than email.

404
00:18:00,552 --> 00:18:03,634
But you know, so choosing the right channel of information

405
00:18:03,654 --> 00:18:05,215
at the right time is really important.

406
00:18:05,835 --> 00:18:07,416
So now, when it comes to scaling,

407
00:18:09,137 --> 00:18:10,897
people often feel like as their studio's growing,

408
00:18:10,917 --> 00:18:12,938
you hear a lot of thoughts about scale.

409
00:18:13,179 --> 00:18:14,739
There are some people who say, you can never

410
00:18:14,779 --> 00:18:16,380
do a good game with more than five people.

411
00:18:17,085 --> 00:18:20,389
and then as a people's it never do again more twenty people

412
00:18:20,870 --> 00:18:24,795
and and uh... but then you see big studios to do the games and what's

413
00:18:24,936 --> 00:18:25,476
exactly

414
00:18:25,777 --> 00:18:26,317
is happening

415
00:18:26,678 --> 00:18:29,542
and why is it different with more people what is it the changes

416
00:18:29,983 --> 00:18:31,705
well the key thing is just simply

417
00:18:32,105 --> 00:18:32,366
this

418
00:18:34,716 --> 00:18:37,238
The number of interactions between people

419
00:18:37,779 --> 00:18:40,101
goes up in kind of an exponential way,

420
00:18:40,301 --> 00:18:42,322
technically the triangle numbers pattern, right?

421
00:18:43,443 --> 00:18:46,206
Three people working together, you just, it's easy, right?

422
00:18:46,306 --> 00:18:48,688
You just, the channels of communication are really simple.

423
00:18:48,728 --> 00:18:49,889
But even when you get up to something

424
00:18:49,929 --> 00:18:51,190
as small as seven people,

425
00:18:51,670 --> 00:18:54,993
like look at all those different paths of information.

426
00:18:55,293 --> 00:18:56,694
And this becomes really important.

427
00:18:56,995 --> 00:18:58,356
If you were on a team of five people,

428
00:18:58,536 --> 00:18:59,617
every day when you come in,

429
00:19:00,037 --> 00:19:02,479
you all talk to each other every day.

430
00:19:03,232 --> 00:19:04,493
When you're on a team of 20 people,

431
00:19:04,894 --> 00:19:07,337
you're not necessarily going to talk to everybody every day.

432
00:19:07,598 --> 00:19:09,560
But you'll probably talk to everybody,

433
00:19:09,961 --> 00:19:12,184
at least have some minor contact with them once a week.

434
00:19:12,764 --> 00:19:16,525
Once you get up to 50 people, you might go four weeks, six weeks, and there might be

435
00:19:16,585 --> 00:19:20,506
somebody in the studio who you have not exchanged one word with in all that time.

436
00:19:21,106 --> 00:19:24,667
And it may be that they have some super important piece of information for you, but you wouldn't

437
00:19:24,707 --> 00:19:29,009
know it because, you know, because the place is big.

438
00:19:29,849 --> 00:19:35,111
And so what we do is we try and set up organizational structures in order to try and get the right

439
00:19:35,151 --> 00:19:38,652
information to the right places at the right time, because it's not going to happen simply

440
00:19:38,732 --> 00:19:39,632
organically this way.

441
00:19:40,893 --> 00:19:42,094
So this is why we have org charts.

442
00:19:42,135 --> 00:19:44,917
Here's a picture of the org chart for Shell Games.

443
00:19:46,558 --> 00:19:50,301
And org charts are typically organized by discipline.

444
00:19:51,202 --> 00:19:53,344
We've got our production team, and our engineering team,

445
00:19:53,364 --> 00:19:54,705
and our design team, and our art team,

446
00:19:55,326 --> 00:19:56,567
and our operations team.

447
00:19:57,427 --> 00:19:59,469
And that's pretty simple and straightforward.

448
00:19:59,589 --> 00:20:01,831
But nowhere in there do you see reflected

449
00:20:01,931 --> 00:20:03,072
anything about our projects.

450
00:20:03,713 --> 00:20:05,774
We do six to eight projects at a time.

451
00:20:06,715 --> 00:20:11,179
But you sure couldn't figure that out by looking at this organizational chart because the point of this

452
00:20:11,699 --> 00:20:13,921
Organization is not to talk about projects

453
00:20:14,121 --> 00:20:19,606
But to talk about specific discipline things to talk about things that have to do with art or talk about design

454
00:20:19,866 --> 00:20:23,790
So a lot this is really very much a chart about mentoring and just sort of getting

455
00:20:23,850 --> 00:20:29,094
Information to the right people about their discipline and so for studios to do more than one project

456
00:20:29,134 --> 00:20:33,098
This is why it's become very common to use a form of matrix management

457
00:20:34,002 --> 00:20:35,482
Matrix management is a simple idea.

458
00:20:35,502 --> 00:20:38,763
The idea is that you sort of report to two people

459
00:20:38,863 --> 00:20:39,503
when you're on a team.

460
00:20:39,763 --> 00:20:40,383
You report up.

461
00:20:40,483 --> 00:20:42,404
If you're a programmer, you report up

462
00:20:42,444 --> 00:20:44,724
to the head of engineering or head of programming, whatever.

463
00:20:45,204 --> 00:20:47,765
And you work with them on things that

464
00:20:47,805 --> 00:20:50,325
are about long-term mentoring and coaching.

465
00:20:50,686 --> 00:20:52,166
But on your project, someone else

466
00:20:52,246 --> 00:20:53,266
is in charge of your project.

467
00:20:54,566 --> 00:20:57,447
At our place, we always have a producer and a director

468
00:20:57,587 --> 00:20:59,007
at the head of every project.

469
00:20:59,808 --> 00:21:03,170
The director is responsible for the creative vision and making sure it's great.

470
00:21:03,450 --> 00:21:07,632
The producer is responsible for making sure it's done on time and that everyone has everything they need.

471
00:21:08,192 --> 00:21:11,735
Now some people say to me, that's a bad idea. You can't have two people in charge of a project.

472
00:21:12,195 --> 00:21:14,096
That's like having two gods. It doesn't work.

473
00:21:15,377 --> 00:21:18,138
And I say, no. I think it's more like having two parents.

474
00:21:18,899 --> 00:21:20,800
It's kind of a good idea sometimes.

475
00:21:21,140 --> 00:21:22,401
And there's a lot of good reasons for that.

476
00:21:22,441 --> 00:21:23,902
They have different areas of expertise.

477
00:21:24,222 --> 00:21:26,343
The people running your project are focused

478
00:21:26,703 --> 00:21:27,404
on two different things.

479
00:21:27,584 --> 00:21:29,845
And then similarly, backing out to the matrix management

480
00:21:29,885 --> 00:21:31,666
point of view, there's the people in charge of your

481
00:21:31,686 --> 00:21:33,467
project and the people in charge of your discipline.

482
00:21:33,708 --> 00:21:35,509
And it's good to be able to talk to the two of them about

483
00:21:35,549 --> 00:21:36,189
two different things.

484
00:21:37,492 --> 00:21:39,333
people at the head of your project about project issues,

485
00:21:39,433 --> 00:21:41,195
and the person at the head of your department

486
00:21:41,215 --> 00:21:42,295
about longer-term issues.

487
00:21:42,796 --> 00:21:44,477
And if you've got a problem with one of them,

488
00:21:44,857 --> 00:21:46,658
you can go to the other and say, man,

489
00:21:47,038 --> 00:21:49,300
you know, I'm hitting a logjam with this guy.

490
00:21:49,360 --> 00:21:50,040
Can you help me?

491
00:21:50,380 --> 00:21:52,262
And then they can often help you out.

492
00:21:53,502 --> 00:21:57,025
So the reason matrix management seems to be a good idea

493
00:21:57,045 --> 00:21:59,126
and is used frequently is because it

494
00:21:59,146 --> 00:22:01,287
allows two different kinds of channels of information.

495
00:22:03,715 --> 00:22:07,837
So organizational structure is one tool for managing your flow.

496
00:22:08,437 --> 00:22:10,278
A second one is office space.

