00:22:26,986 --> 00:22:27,946
It's not well designed.

507
00:22:28,047 --> 00:22:30,008
Now, it is a hard, hard design problem.

508
00:22:30,929 --> 00:22:35,173
But if you work at it, you can certainly make it better.

509
00:22:35,213 --> 00:22:37,095
So there's a lot of things to think about when you're

510
00:22:37,115 --> 00:22:38,176
designing your office space.

511
00:22:38,897 --> 00:22:41,419
One thing is to realize that a little distance is

512
00:22:41,679 --> 00:22:43,561
a lot of distance.

513
00:22:43,741 --> 00:22:46,304
So here's an illustration of a thing I literally saw right

514
00:22:46,364 --> 00:22:48,946
outside my desk one day.

515
00:22:48,966 --> 00:22:50,548
We had a project.

516
00:22:50,768 --> 00:22:51,889
There were four people working on it.

517
00:22:52,505 --> 00:22:54,407
and three of them were sitting right next to each other like that.

518
00:22:54,727 --> 00:22:57,710
And then in the middle, you see this kind of a low counter,

519
00:22:57,890 --> 00:23:00,492
that green bar up the middle, was just a low counter.

520
00:23:00,552 --> 00:23:01,133
No big deal.

521
00:23:01,233 --> 00:23:02,574
Like people stored things in it.

522
00:23:03,075 --> 00:23:04,396
And on the other side of that counter

523
00:23:04,676 --> 00:23:05,937
was this other guy with his other desk.

524
00:23:06,218 --> 00:23:10,762
Couldn't have been more than 15 feet, OK, from those three

525
00:23:10,782 --> 00:23:11,703
desks to that one desk.

526
00:23:12,504 --> 00:23:15,986
And but we were observing that there was some bad communication problem

527
00:23:16,386 --> 00:23:18,448
where that one guy kept getting left out of the loop.

528
00:23:18,888 --> 00:23:20,549
And we're like, man, that guy, is he dope?

529
00:23:20,849 --> 00:23:21,750
Why isn't he talking?

530
00:23:21,810 --> 00:23:22,570
Is he just lazy?

531
00:23:22,650 --> 00:23:23,171
Is he ignorant?

532
00:23:23,631 --> 00:23:26,673
And then just watching, it's like, oh my god, I could see it happening.

533
00:23:26,693 --> 00:23:28,194
Someone would be like, hey, I've got a problem.

534
00:23:28,534 --> 00:23:29,875
And the guy next to him would say, yeah, what is it?

535
00:23:30,075 --> 00:23:31,156
Well, it's this and this and this.

536
00:23:31,196 --> 00:23:32,917
And the guy over there is kind of like, wait, you guys talk?

537
00:23:33,778 --> 00:23:35,418
And you can see he's kind of listening.

538
00:23:35,438 --> 00:23:36,578
He's like, no, I don't want to interrupt him.

539
00:23:36,598 --> 00:23:37,359
I'll get back to work.

540
00:23:37,719 --> 00:23:39,019
And he was just left out of the loop.

541
00:23:39,259 --> 00:23:41,220
We simply moved his desk over next to the others,

542
00:23:41,600 --> 00:23:44,100
and the problems got so much better.

543
00:23:45,040 --> 00:23:47,841
So thinking about that is really important.

544
00:23:48,841 --> 00:23:50,402
A lot of notable companies have really

545
00:23:50,422 --> 00:23:51,762
gotten aggressive about office space.

546
00:23:51,822 --> 00:23:53,322
Pixar is one that's very notable.

547
00:23:53,842 --> 00:23:56,263
A lot of times you walk into some big fancy company,

548
00:23:56,323 --> 00:23:57,843
and you go into this big open space.

549
00:23:57,983 --> 00:23:59,404
And you do that here when you go to Pixar.

550
00:23:59,704 --> 00:24:01,864
And that open space is full of weird sculptures

551
00:24:02,104 --> 00:24:03,405
and creepy security guards.

552
00:24:03,845 --> 00:24:07,066
and like you don't really see it doesn't have any point or purpose of the into

553
00:24:07,166 --> 00:24:08,506
intimidate you or whatever

554
00:24:09,246 --> 00:24:10,407
when you walk into pixar

555
00:24:10,867 --> 00:24:14,908
you're in the cafeteria let me know that the band is in the places people sit and

556
00:24:15,028 --> 00:24:17,249
eat in the cafeteria you walk right in

557
00:24:18,369 --> 00:24:20,470
it's it's the central hub of the building and

558
00:24:20,970 --> 00:24:24,011
the whole space is designed very much to get people to cross through this space

559
00:24:24,071 --> 00:24:25,371
as many times as possible

560
00:24:25,731 --> 00:24:28,332
all the bathrooms for example are in the central space

561
00:24:28,712 --> 00:24:31,353
the offices are often like always the go out to the sides

562
00:24:31,693 --> 00:24:34,195
and people are forced to cross through this many times.

563
00:24:34,275 --> 00:24:36,777
All the meeting rooms, you see all those glass walled things

564
00:24:36,837 --> 00:24:37,077
up there?

565
00:24:37,317 --> 00:24:38,098
Those are the meeting rooms.

566
00:24:38,118 --> 00:24:39,699
You can stand in the middle and kind of see,

567
00:24:40,039 --> 00:24:41,400
oh, there's where that guy is.

568
00:24:41,500 --> 00:24:42,661
Oh, look, there's a vacant meeting room.

569
00:24:42,941 --> 00:24:44,543
You can see all that stuff.

570
00:24:46,064 --> 00:24:47,545
It's very, very much designed.

571
00:24:48,486 --> 00:24:50,647
Interestingly, Steve Jobs was very, very involved

572
00:24:50,727 --> 00:24:52,609
in the design of this particular space.

573
00:24:53,814 --> 00:24:56,555
We've tried to take a very similar approach in our space,

574
00:24:56,595 --> 00:24:58,036
trying to have things be very, very open.

575
00:24:58,056 --> 00:24:59,997
You know, we don't have 1,500 people like Pixar does.

576
00:25:00,017 --> 00:25:00,337
We have about 100.

577
00:25:01,638 --> 00:25:04,420
But we are big fans of open plan.

578
00:25:05,040 --> 00:25:08,222
And so you can see there's most of the folks kind of

579
00:25:08,302 --> 00:25:08,942
working down there.

580
00:25:09,202 --> 00:25:11,764
The way groups are organized is by project.

581
00:25:12,144 --> 00:25:13,664
We move desks around all the time.

582
00:25:14,045 --> 00:25:15,825
Anytime there's new projects, we get desks

583
00:25:16,085 --> 00:25:17,545
so people can get together.

584
00:25:17,926 --> 00:25:20,046
And you'd think we would maybe organize them

585
00:25:20,106 --> 00:25:22,667
by those kind of islands that you see,

586
00:25:22,887 --> 00:25:25,867
but they're really organized by canals, okay?

587
00:25:26,128 --> 00:25:28,208
So people with back-to-back are the ones

588
00:25:28,268 --> 00:25:29,708
working on projects together because

589
00:25:29,988 --> 00:25:31,449
someone could say, hey, can you take a look at this?

590
00:25:31,669 --> 00:25:33,549
And they can just turn around and take a look.

591
00:25:33,809 --> 00:25:35,910
It's very different than, oh, can you walk all the way around

592
00:25:35,930 --> 00:25:37,390
the island and come and see us?

593
00:25:37,630 --> 00:25:40,151
It's just a small design thing, but it makes a big difference.

594
00:25:41,606 --> 00:25:43,068
Okay, so office space is really important.

595
00:25:43,088 --> 00:25:44,391
There's so, there's a, that's, that's,

596
00:25:44,631 --> 00:25:46,213
I could talk about that for, for days and days.

597
00:25:46,614 --> 00:25:47,916
But let's talk about other things.

598
00:25:48,377 --> 00:25:51,923
Another really important flow management tool is ritual.

599
00:25:52,483 --> 00:25:56,330
And our most common ritual is meetings, right?

600
00:25:58,532 --> 00:26:02,374
And people mostly don't feel great about meetings,

601
00:26:02,514 --> 00:26:04,534
because there's a lot of bad meetings, because no one

602
00:26:04,594 --> 00:26:06,195
bothers to design them.

603
00:26:06,735 --> 00:26:08,596
Well-designed meetings are awesome.

604
00:26:09,556 --> 00:26:10,817
You go in, you get stuff done.

605
00:26:10,937 --> 00:26:12,297
It was like, oh, that really helped me.

606
00:26:12,317 --> 00:26:14,038
You come out thinking, man, now I know what's going on.

607
00:26:14,298 --> 00:26:15,018
That really helped me.

608
00:26:15,278 --> 00:26:17,039
Now I can work with more confidence.

609
00:26:17,079 --> 00:26:18,780
I know exactly what's going on.

610
00:26:19,040 --> 00:26:20,680
Badly designed meetings are awesome.

611
00:26:21,258 --> 00:26:22,938
I don't know, the ninth level of hell.

612
00:26:22,998 --> 00:26:24,459
They're really, really bad.

613
00:26:25,499 --> 00:26:27,000
And there's a lot of ways to design meetings.

614
00:26:27,060 --> 00:26:29,120
People who do, actually, hands up, people who do Agile.

615
00:26:29,341 --> 00:26:30,421
I'm curious.

616
00:26:30,561 --> 00:26:30,921
Look at this.

617
00:26:30,961 --> 00:26:31,861
There's a lot of Agile here.

618
00:26:31,881 --> 00:26:33,902
And there's a lot of people like, I don't do Agile.

619
00:26:33,962 --> 00:26:34,602
Maybe I should.

620
00:26:34,622 --> 00:26:35,102
I don't know.

621
00:26:35,703 --> 00:26:36,603
Or I hate Agile.

622
00:26:36,623 --> 00:26:37,283
It's stupid jerks.

623
00:26:37,363 --> 00:26:38,163
You know, it's a lot of things.

624
00:26:38,564 --> 00:26:40,664
But anyway, one of the key elements of Agile

625
00:26:40,804 --> 00:26:42,345
is the notion of the Scrum meeting.

626
00:26:42,405 --> 00:26:45,066
And this is very, very much a designed meeting.

627
00:26:45,346 --> 00:26:46,366
The idea is it's very short.

628
00:26:46,626 --> 00:26:49,107
You're talking about a very small number of things.

629
00:26:50,020 --> 00:26:52,061
And often, part of the design is people say,

630
00:26:52,101 --> 00:26:53,201
this is a standing meeting.

631
00:26:53,221 --> 00:26:55,162
There'll be no sitting down in this meeting

632
00:26:55,322 --> 00:26:57,143
because we want to get this done and get back to work

633
00:26:57,203 --> 00:27:00,304
and not turn this into a waste of time.

634
00:27:00,724 --> 00:27:01,324
And so that's cool.

635
00:27:01,364 --> 00:27:03,585
Look at these happy people having their scrum meeting

636
00:27:03,645 --> 00:27:04,025
right here.

637
00:27:04,965 --> 00:27:05,746
And you know why they're happy?

638
00:27:05,766 --> 00:27:07,646
Because they're out of those horrible cubicles

639
00:27:07,666 --> 00:27:08,086
that they're in.

640
00:27:08,106 --> 00:27:08,686
Look at those.

641
00:27:09,407 --> 00:27:11,367
Those are like the worst of both worlds

642
00:27:11,447 --> 00:27:13,008
when it comes to cubicles, right?

643
00:27:14,869 --> 00:27:16,489
Because look at the height of those.

644
00:27:16,749 --> 00:27:17,849
You go back and sit in that.

645
00:27:18,550 --> 00:27:19,891
Do you have noise protection?

646
00:27:20,271 --> 00:27:22,193
Are you like, I'm in my isolated pod?

647
00:27:22,433 --> 00:27:22,593
No.

648
00:27:22,853 --> 00:27:24,995
There's all the potential noise of the studio is there.

649
00:27:25,195 --> 00:27:27,557
Can you see where anyone is or what anyone is doing?

650
00:27:27,917 --> 00:27:28,077
No.

651
00:27:28,357 --> 00:27:29,879
Even if you stand up, you can't.

652
00:27:29,899 --> 00:27:32,200
You've got to peek up over the wall.

653
00:27:32,421 --> 00:27:35,083
So it's like this illusion of, I have a big important office,

654
00:27:35,523 --> 00:27:38,425
but with all the horrible aspects of that.

655
00:27:39,026 --> 00:27:42,408
I am not a fan of the six foot high cube wall.

656
00:27:43,409 --> 00:27:46,271
OK, so talking more broadly about Agile.

657
00:27:47,652 --> 00:27:51,556
Agile is really just a system of coordinating and organizing

658
00:27:51,677 --> 00:27:53,078
information flow.

659
00:27:53,587 --> 00:27:53,767
right?

660
00:27:53,967 --> 00:27:55,968
You've got your product backlog.

661
00:27:56,228 --> 00:27:57,509
These are all the things that we would

662
00:27:57,549 --> 00:27:58,529
like to put into the game.

663
00:27:59,049 --> 00:28:02,991
And then you organize sprints, these little two, three, four

664
00:28:03,031 --> 00:28:06,672
week sessions where you have a very specific goal.

665
00:28:06,932 --> 00:28:08,012
Everyone knows the goal.

666
00:28:08,052 --> 00:28:09,513
You've communicated the goal clearly.

667
00:28:09,613 --> 00:28:11,874
We're going to deliver this at the end of 30 days.

668
00:28:12,694 --> 00:28:16,315
And then once a day, you have your Scrum meeting

669
00:28:16,555 --> 00:28:17,836
where what did you do yesterday?

670
00:28:17,856 --> 00:28:18,536
What did you do today?

671
00:28:18,576 --> 00:28:19,456
What problems are you having?

672
00:28:19,536 --> 00:28:19,897
OK, good.

673
00:28:19,917 --> 00:28:20,617
Let's get back to work.

674
00:28:20,957 --> 00:28:21,617
And let's change it.

675
00:28:22,077 --> 00:28:23,418
so that we know what we're doing.

676
00:28:24,818 --> 00:28:27,539
And that's all very much about organizing information flow

677
00:28:27,579 --> 00:28:31,480
about what we're doing so that you can optimize continually

678
00:28:31,880 --> 00:28:32,480
on the project.

679
00:28:32,740 --> 00:28:34,521
Fred Brooks, author of the Mythical Man-Month,

680
00:28:35,681 --> 00:28:38,762
you know, he was looking at how bad software projects tend to go

681
00:28:39,582 --> 00:28:40,563
and someone was saying,

682
00:28:40,583 --> 00:28:42,043
look, I don't understand you software people.

683
00:28:42,083 --> 00:28:43,404
You said it was going to be out by this date

684
00:28:43,864 --> 00:28:46,164
and you were a year late.

685
00:28:47,045 --> 00:28:48,785
I can understand somebody being two days late

686
00:28:48,945 --> 00:28:50,946
or a week late, a year late.

687
00:28:51,824 --> 00:28:53,926
How are you a year late for something?

688
00:28:54,587 --> 00:28:56,429
Yeah, don't worry, honey, I'll meet you at 5 o'clock.

689
00:28:56,529 --> 00:28:57,870
Oh, sorry, I'm a year late.

690
00:28:59,632 --> 00:28:59,893
Right?

691
00:29:00,813 --> 00:29:04,357
And his answer is, you get a year late one day at a time.

692
00:29:04,497 --> 00:29:05,678
That is how you do it.

693
00:29:05,959 --> 00:29:08,521
And so the idea is to do this sort of daily management so

694
00:29:08,541 --> 00:29:11,484
that you can steer the project, get the right information to

695
00:29:11,504 --> 00:29:12,085
the right people.

696
00:29:13,022 --> 00:29:14,143
and steer your project.

697
00:29:14,423 --> 00:29:17,984
OK, so Agile is really a system of information flow.

698
00:29:18,744 --> 00:29:21,625
So another popular thing, popular with some people,

699
00:29:21,665 --> 00:29:25,287
less popular with others, is the notion of 360 feedback.

700
00:29:25,847 --> 00:29:29,048
People tend to dread feedback reviews at work.

701
00:29:29,428 --> 00:29:31,169
Most of the time, the people giving the reviews

702
00:29:31,269 --> 00:29:33,590
don't know what they're doing because they're not

703
00:29:33,670 --> 00:29:34,430
experts in this.

704
00:29:34,770 --> 00:29:35,890
It's super awkward.

705
00:29:35,910 --> 00:29:37,371
You're having this awkward conversation

706
00:29:37,391 --> 00:29:39,532
about what you're good at and what you're bad at.

707
00:29:39,992 --> 00:29:41,232
And like, do I trust this guy?

708
00:29:41,272 --> 00:29:42,373
And is this guy going to believe me?

709
00:29:44,126 --> 00:29:46,547
Often this is because it's badly designed.

710
00:29:47,047 --> 00:29:49,407
Well-designed 360 feedback is an opportunity

711
00:29:49,447 --> 00:29:51,528
to collect feedback from all the people

712
00:29:51,568 --> 00:29:54,009
that somebody works with and get all the information

713
00:29:54,269 --> 00:29:56,790
that maybe they say to each other, but maybe they don't,

714
00:29:56,810 --> 00:29:58,670
because it's really awkward.

715
00:29:59,130 --> 00:30:01,311
Like, dude, your BO is killing me, right?

716
00:30:01,671 --> 00:30:04,072
That is not a conversation that two employees will often have.

717
00:30:04,411 --> 00:30:07,833
But sometimes it's the sort of thing that will come out in anonymous 360 feedback.

718
00:30:08,113 --> 00:30:12,295
If it's anonymous, and you can guarantee the information is not going to go,

719
00:30:12,395 --> 00:30:17,138
it will often go up to one of the managers who can kind of have this conversation.

720
00:30:17,458 --> 00:30:20,680
Which makes it essential that the people who are giving these reviews

721
00:30:21,381 --> 00:30:25,723
know how to do them well and understand how to do it tactfully and usefully.

722
00:30:26,263 --> 00:30:30,806
If a good manager collects the information from a bunch of people, processes it,

723
00:30:31,206 --> 00:30:35,808
so that they figure out, okay, these are the useful things I want to pass on and discuss

724
00:30:36,108 --> 00:30:38,209
and hear this person's feedback about,

725
00:30:38,229 --> 00:30:42,651
and it becomes a conversation. And if you do this right, people don't dread

726
00:30:42,891 --> 00:30:46,813
the reviews. They get useful information that helps them,

727
00:30:47,113 --> 00:30:50,134
and it can be very, very positive, but you have to take it

728
00:30:50,334 --> 00:30:53,396
seriously. One thing we recently did, because we realized...

729
00:30:53,976 --> 00:30:56,637
you know it's tough to fit these in your like i want to focus on the game i don't

730
00:30:56,657 --> 00:30:58,357
want to focus on filling out forms and

731
00:30:58,877 --> 00:31:01,518
and um... and i sit down having uncomfortable conversations

732
00:31:01,718 --> 00:31:02,859
c ten to put it off

733
00:31:03,219 --> 00:31:04,339
and we've been doing that

734
00:31:04,639 --> 00:31:06,060
and that really sends this message that

735
00:31:06,400 --> 00:31:08,020
if you put this off it must not be important

736
00:31:08,240 --> 00:31:10,061
but it's super important this is all about

737
00:31:10,401 --> 00:31:12,822
making everybody the best person they can be

738
00:31:13,222 --> 00:31:17,183
so we've rescheduled it now instead of doing all once a year or uh... once every

739
00:31:17,323 --> 00:31:17,423
uh...

740
00:31:18,223 --> 00:31:18,803
uh... six months

741
00:31:19,663 --> 00:31:22,065
We spread them out so they fit into people's schedules

742
00:31:22,385 --> 00:31:23,706
so that they're not an intrusion.

743
00:31:24,086 --> 00:31:25,347
And that's made it much more comfortable.

744
00:31:25,467 --> 00:31:27,469
And again, it helps send the signal that, look,

745
00:31:27,489 --> 00:31:28,289
this is important to us.

746
00:31:28,309 --> 00:31:29,170
We make time for this.

747
00:31:29,850 --> 00:31:31,371
So there are many, many types of meetings.

748
00:31:31,511 --> 00:31:32,592
Any kind of meeting that you have

749
00:31:32,632 --> 00:31:34,434
is a sort of ritual that your company has.

750
00:31:34,474 --> 00:31:35,775
And you want to design that so it's good.

751
00:31:36,155 --> 00:31:37,396
Some of those are short and daily.

752
00:31:37,516 --> 00:31:38,436
Many of them are weekly.

753
00:31:38,716 --> 00:31:40,397
Some of them you do every, like, four times a year.

754
00:31:41,138 --> 00:31:42,539
And then there's some you do annually.

755
00:31:42,619 --> 00:31:44,560
One that we do that was worked out really well for us

756
00:31:44,900 --> 00:31:46,121
is this notion of Jam Week.

757
00:31:46,161 --> 00:31:48,822
We stop everything that the studio is doing once a year,

758
00:31:49,463 --> 00:31:51,624
and we say, you know what?

759
00:31:51,664 --> 00:31:52,945
Let's have people work on projects

760
00:31:53,005 --> 00:31:54,586
that they are excited about,

761
00:31:54,626 --> 00:31:56,687
that they think might be good to go somewhere.

