00:31:56,987 --> 00:31:59,229
You know, just something good could come with this.

763
00:31:59,409 --> 00:32:03,913
Either my personal development, or maybe just something

764
00:32:03,933 --> 00:32:06,094
that would be really good for the studio.

765
00:32:06,495 --> 00:32:09,057
Now, is this an information flow management situation?

766
00:32:09,137 --> 00:32:09,797
It totally is.

767
00:32:09,877 --> 00:32:11,699
People have ideas for things that they'd like to do,

768
00:32:11,979 --> 00:32:13,780
and it's blocked because it's not

769
00:32:13,840 --> 00:32:15,281
part of their regular daily project.

770
00:32:15,742 --> 00:32:18,484
This creates an opportunity for like, hey,

771
00:32:18,524 --> 00:32:20,165
that cool idea bouncing around in your head.

772
00:32:20,525 --> 00:32:21,425
We're making time.

773
00:32:21,666 --> 00:32:22,406
It's important to us.

774
00:32:22,426 --> 00:32:25,109
We're making time for it to come out and for you to experiment

775
00:32:25,169 --> 00:32:26,169
and connect with other people.

776
00:32:26,450 --> 00:32:27,310
And good things come of it.

777
00:32:27,350 --> 00:32:32,334
Last year, one of ours was this Enemy Mind game that came out.

778
00:32:32,435 --> 00:32:35,057
And everybody liked it so much, after a one-week prototype,

