00:32:42,963 --> 00:32:43,824
have in Kickstarter.

784
00:32:44,204 --> 00:32:46,686
And it's in its final week, so please back it.

785
00:32:47,387 --> 00:32:49,649
I think we're going to make it, but it's a little close.

786
00:32:49,709 --> 00:32:52,592
So anyway, if you could back that, that would be great.

787
00:32:52,912 --> 00:32:55,274
Anyway, but it's exciting.

788
00:32:55,334 --> 00:32:58,137
I mean, people get really energized

789
00:32:58,277 --> 00:33:00,339
when the things they're excited about come to light.

790
00:33:00,419 --> 00:33:02,421
And you have to make channels for that to happen.

791
00:33:02,862 --> 00:33:04,303
But there's lots of other rituals.

792
00:33:04,543 --> 00:33:06,926
There's this great story I read about on the Harvard Business

793
00:33:06,946 --> 00:33:07,666
Review I just love.

794
00:33:08,067 --> 00:33:08,908
This company where

795
00:33:09,388 --> 00:33:11,290
They didn't have a modern coffee pot.

796
00:33:11,330 --> 00:33:14,072
They had this clanky, old, percolator coffee pot.

797
00:33:14,393 --> 00:33:16,755
Only two people in the office knew how to operate it properly

798
00:33:16,795 --> 00:33:18,216
and not get grounds in all the coffee.

799
00:33:19,698 --> 00:33:23,799
And so when they would make coffee, they would get the coffee going and they'd say,

800
00:33:24,139 --> 00:33:26,140
you know, hey everybody, coffee's ready.

801
00:33:26,200 --> 00:33:28,901
And everybody would come for coffee and everyone would hang out in the kitchen,

802
00:33:28,961 --> 00:33:32,262
chatting and stuff, and a lot of useful information was flowing around.

803
00:33:32,682 --> 00:33:36,583
And the guy who was the head of the studio, he's like, yeah, no, that's great.

804
00:33:36,603 --> 00:33:37,043
Look at this.

805
00:33:37,063 --> 00:33:37,763
This is so cool.

806
00:33:37,803 --> 00:33:39,884
I love our little coffee times and everybody's talking.

807
00:33:40,244 --> 00:33:42,225
This is cool. This is cool and good and useful.

808
00:33:42,525 --> 00:33:45,786
But jeez, I feel terrible that everyone's got this terrible coffee pot.

809
00:33:46,266 --> 00:33:48,446
Right? So you know what I'm going to do, because coffee time is so important,

810
00:33:48,466 --> 00:33:50,647
I'm going to get one of these fancy, modern, K-cup things.

811
00:33:50,687 --> 00:33:53,168
That way you guys have awesome coffee, customized coffee,

812
00:33:53,548 --> 00:33:56,028
just the coffee you want, any time you want,

813
00:33:56,589 --> 00:33:58,809
one cup at a time, and coffee time went away.

814
00:33:59,589 --> 00:34:03,751
And this really useful ritual that had been part of an information passing thing

815
00:34:03,771 --> 00:34:06,811
in the studio went away, and it led to problems.

816
00:34:06,991 --> 00:34:09,172
These things are super, super subtle.

817
00:34:10,185 --> 00:34:13,386
And I know it's silly to kind of talk about things centering around food, but food is

818
00:34:13,447 --> 00:34:15,488
super important to us as humans.

819
00:34:15,968 --> 00:34:21,111
In our triune structure of the brain, the back part, the most basic part, is like very

820
00:34:21,151 --> 00:34:25,613
interested in food and it has strong opinions about food, right?

821
00:34:26,093 --> 00:34:28,975
Go into any college cafeteria, right?

822
00:34:29,215 --> 00:34:31,977
You go into a college classroom and you look at like people sitting around and you're like,

823
00:34:32,017 --> 00:34:33,958
wow, look at this international mix of people.

824
00:34:34,298 --> 00:34:36,939
And then you go to the cafeteria and look at the segregation

825
00:34:36,979 --> 00:34:38,179
that happens in the cafeteria.

826
00:34:38,639 --> 00:34:39,900
Because there's something in us that's like,

827
00:34:39,980 --> 00:34:41,500
I want to eat with people like me,

828
00:34:42,101 --> 00:34:45,182
because those other people might take my food.

829
00:34:45,622 --> 00:34:47,463
And then further, it goes the other way.

830
00:34:48,343 --> 00:34:49,223
It goes the other way.

831
00:34:49,303 --> 00:34:52,744
If you eat a meal with someone you haven't eaten a meal with

832
00:34:52,784 --> 00:34:56,046
before, your brain's like, that dude didn't take my food.

833
00:34:58,086 --> 00:35:00,807
I can trust that guy on a kind of a deep, fundamental level.

834
00:35:03,537 --> 00:35:05,978
So a lot of studios, they do a thing where, we're so cool, man.

835
00:35:06,018 --> 00:35:07,599
We got free lunches every day.

836
00:35:07,659 --> 00:35:10,680
We got an omelet chef who comes at 3 o'clock every day.

837
00:35:10,740 --> 00:35:12,460
And you never have to leave the studio.

838
00:35:12,500 --> 00:35:13,201
Isn't that great?

839
00:35:13,721 --> 00:35:14,501
No, that's not great.

840
00:35:14,801 --> 00:35:15,701
Never leave the studio.

841
00:35:15,721 --> 00:35:18,722
It means you're kind of stuck in the same rut all the time.

842
00:35:19,143 --> 00:35:19,703
And what do you do?

843
00:35:19,763 --> 00:35:21,183
You go in, you're the omelet chef.

844
00:35:21,203 --> 00:35:21,704
You get your omelet.

845
00:35:21,724 --> 00:35:22,584
You go back to your desk.

846
00:35:22,624 --> 00:35:25,025
There's no conversation, right?

847
00:35:25,385 --> 00:35:26,685
So I don't like to do that.

848
00:35:26,725 --> 00:35:28,586
We do that a little bit, a little free food once in a while.

849
00:35:28,926 --> 00:35:30,206
But like every day?

850
00:35:30,578 --> 00:35:34,587
Because what you want is you want people to get together and go out of the studio,

851
00:35:34,607 --> 00:35:38,996
because that changes their point of view, and you want them to kind of bond up in social situations.

852
00:35:41,310 --> 00:35:45,132
The hunting party, man, that's an old fundamental notion.

853
00:35:45,352 --> 00:35:45,952
And you see it.

854
00:35:46,653 --> 00:35:48,914
Someone's like, hey, you guys want to get frozen yogurt?

855
00:35:49,094 --> 00:35:50,455
I'm like, oh, OK, yeah, let's all go.

856
00:35:50,675 --> 00:35:51,215
And they're going.

857
00:35:51,255 --> 00:35:52,336
And you see that walk.

858
00:35:52,356 --> 00:35:53,417
There's that walk they're doing.

859
00:35:54,277 --> 00:35:56,418
They're just going down to hunt down to host

860
00:35:56,458 --> 00:35:57,479
his Twinkie or whatever.

861
00:35:58,820 --> 00:35:59,640
But still, you see it.

862
00:35:59,660 --> 00:36:02,022
And there's a sort of bonding that happens around it.

863
00:36:02,742 --> 00:36:03,182
And that happens.

864
00:36:03,222 --> 00:36:05,123
And a lot of useful conversation happens there.

865
00:36:05,604 --> 00:36:08,245
So when you give out free food at a studio,

866
00:36:08,265 --> 00:36:10,867
you're often blocking really useful information flow.

867
00:36:12,247 --> 00:36:14,008
Also, I'm very cheap.

868
00:36:14,428 --> 00:36:14,709
OK.

869
00:36:16,310 --> 00:36:20,852
So another flow management tool is just social factors.

870
00:36:21,092 --> 00:36:24,635
So much about information is about who likes who and who

871
00:36:24,715 --> 00:36:25,595
likes talking to whom.

872
00:36:25,895 --> 00:36:26,696
Look at this team.

873
00:36:27,436 --> 00:36:28,817
That looks like a team that is going to

874
00:36:28,857 --> 00:36:31,019
communicate pretty well.

875
00:36:31,259 --> 00:36:32,660
You can tell just by kind of looking.

876
00:36:32,840 --> 00:36:35,362
Like, these guys are very, very comfortable with each other.

877
00:36:35,402 --> 00:36:39,287
They're going to be, it's going to be easy for them to share information with each other.

878
00:36:39,527 --> 00:36:40,988
So now there's been a lot of research about this.

879
00:36:41,249 --> 00:36:44,572
Some of the most interesting, I think, is this research by Dr. Anita Woolley.

880
00:36:46,134 --> 00:36:48,436
And it's all about the notion of collective intelligence.

881
00:36:48,697 --> 00:36:50,859
We've had intelligence tests for years and years and years.

882
00:36:51,139 --> 00:36:53,502
We understand about measuring individual intelligence.

883
00:36:54,182 --> 00:36:56,924
Her question was, what about the intelligence of a group?

884
00:36:57,144 --> 00:36:57,944
How does that work?

885
00:36:58,404 --> 00:37:00,686
Now, a lot of people would say, well, that's easy.

886
00:37:00,786 --> 00:37:02,306
You just take the IQs of everybody in the group

887
00:37:02,467 --> 00:37:03,847
and you average it?

888
00:37:04,548 --> 00:37:05,628
No, you take the maximum?

889
00:37:06,188 --> 00:37:07,149
No, you take the min?

890
00:37:07,369 --> 00:37:07,729
I don't know.

891
00:37:07,869 --> 00:37:08,290
What do you do?

892
00:37:08,750 --> 00:37:10,131
And she found it has nothing to do with that.

893
00:37:10,271 --> 00:37:12,232
The intelligence of the people in the group

894
00:37:12,632 --> 00:37:14,613
individually doesn't matter very much

895
00:37:14,813 --> 00:37:17,234
in terms of the collective intelligence of the group.

896
00:37:17,754 --> 00:37:20,316
Her studies found that there were exactly three factors.

897
00:37:20,776 --> 00:37:24,078
that were critical when it came to the intelligent behavior

898
00:37:24,438 --> 00:37:24,858
of a group.

899
00:37:25,298 --> 00:37:27,960
And she did this by giving groups these different tests.

900
00:37:28,960 --> 00:37:30,821
So here are the three factors she found were really relevant.

901
00:37:31,261 --> 00:37:35,103
The first one is, how do people perform on the eyes test?

902
00:37:35,763 --> 00:37:38,585
Okay? So the eyes test is this interesting test

903
00:37:38,605 --> 00:37:40,005
where you see a lot of pictures like this.

904
00:37:41,266 --> 00:37:42,727
Right? How is she feeling right now?

905
00:37:44,267 --> 00:37:45,228
A, B, C, or D?

906
00:37:46,549 --> 00:37:47,389
So think about that.

907
00:37:47,409 --> 00:37:48,369
See if you got the answer.

908
00:37:49,590 --> 00:37:49,910
All right?

909
00:37:50,960 --> 00:37:58,831
All right. All right. Hands up for A. Hands up for B. Hands up for C. Hands up for D.

910
00:37:59,793 --> 00:38:02,577
Okay. The correct answer is A. Okay.

911
00:38:04,393 --> 00:38:05,634
All right, you can go, Harley.

912
00:38:06,214 --> 00:38:09,657
Anyway, groups that had people who performed really well

913
00:38:09,677 --> 00:38:11,799
on this test, because some people are great at it,

914
00:38:12,099 --> 00:38:13,601
and some people are really bad at it.

915
00:38:13,681 --> 00:38:15,302
Groups who had people who were really good at this

916
00:38:15,722 --> 00:38:16,883
ended up being more intelligent.

917
00:38:17,644 --> 00:38:20,426
Second one, conversational turn-taking.

918
00:38:20,867 --> 00:38:22,608
They measured the amount of times

919
00:38:22,668 --> 00:38:24,209
that people interrupted each other.

920
00:38:25,090 --> 00:38:26,852
Groups that interrupted each other a lot

921
00:38:27,092 --> 00:38:28,693
behaved really stupidly.

922
00:38:30,064 --> 00:38:32,506
Groups that let each other talk, let each other finish,

923
00:38:32,646 --> 00:38:35,609
and had a good balance of conversational turn taking,

924
00:38:35,989 --> 00:38:37,711
they behave very intelligently.

925
00:38:38,611 --> 00:38:40,433
And number three, get ready.

926
00:38:41,614 --> 00:38:42,975
Boom goes the dynamite.

927
00:38:48,800 --> 00:38:52,123
More ladies in the group made it behave smarter.

928
00:38:59,810 --> 00:39:04,893
Now, so, and groups with no ladies, they had certain pathologies that were really, really

929
00:39:04,913 --> 00:39:08,555
bad. And I'm sure some of us have seen this, right? You got a group of dudes all together,

930
00:39:08,895 --> 00:39:12,637
and they're like, we should put in nine features. No, let's put in ten. No, let's put in eleven.

931
00:39:12,797 --> 00:39:17,299
That's awesome, let's do it, right? And then that's how you get a year late, right? That's

932
00:39:17,339 --> 00:39:18,760
totally how that happens.

933
00:39:19,717 --> 00:39:20,837
But there's something that happens.

934
00:39:20,918 --> 00:39:22,479
It's not that if there's a woman in the group,

935
00:39:22,539 --> 00:39:25,481
it's not that the woman comes in and says, no, everybody, stop.

936
00:39:26,161 --> 00:39:27,342
Everybody behaves different.

937
00:39:27,683 --> 00:39:29,824
Again, the back of the brain behaves a little different.

938
00:39:29,944 --> 00:39:31,205
The male brain behaves a little different

939
00:39:31,225 --> 00:39:32,646
when the ladies are around.

940
00:39:33,167 --> 00:39:34,528
It's like, let's put 9, no, 10.

941
00:39:34,668 --> 00:39:37,670
No, actually, maybe we shouldn't be so dangerous all the time.

942
00:39:37,730 --> 00:39:39,612
Maybe we should actually play a little safer.

943
00:39:39,652 --> 00:39:40,572
So there's something in that.

944
00:39:41,073 --> 00:39:42,594
Now, I got together with Dr. Woolley

945
00:39:42,614 --> 00:39:43,975
because I'm like, OK, Dr. Woolley,

946
00:39:43,995 --> 00:39:47,237
I've seen a lot of student teams, a lot, like thousands.

947
00:39:47,798 --> 00:39:47,918
And.

948
00:39:48,898 --> 00:39:50,519
I've seen certain pathologies with all male groups,

949
00:39:51,039 --> 00:39:53,219
and I see certain pathologies with all female groups.

950
00:39:53,339 --> 00:39:56,120
I've seen some all female groups do some really nutty things that

951
00:39:56,140 --> 00:39:57,080
are really, really different.

952
00:39:57,100 --> 00:39:58,941
And she said, yeah, you know, honestly,

953
00:39:59,181 --> 00:40:00,661
we didn't test the all female case.

954
00:40:01,681 --> 00:40:03,242
And she's like, I'm working on it now.

955
00:40:03,262 --> 00:40:04,922
But she's like, yeah, I see the same thing,

956
00:40:05,382 --> 00:40:07,502
that when there's a mix is when it's best.

957
00:40:08,623 --> 00:40:10,283
And so that's really interesting to know

958
00:40:10,383 --> 00:40:11,143
and interesting to think about.

959
00:40:11,383 --> 00:40:13,344
Exactly why is a little unclear, but it's

960
00:40:13,404 --> 00:40:14,124
a thing to think about.

961
00:40:14,224 --> 00:40:16,284
And given the game industry isn't very well balanced

962
00:40:16,304 --> 00:40:18,245
this way, it's something important to consider.

963
00:40:19,919 --> 00:40:21,139
OK, so we got all those things.

964
00:40:21,239 --> 00:40:22,320
Those are some tools you can use.

965
00:40:22,340 --> 00:40:24,460
So now let's talk about what blocks information,

966
00:40:24,480 --> 00:40:27,101
because there's a lot of things that can block information

967
00:40:27,161 --> 00:40:28,021
flow in your studio.

968
00:40:28,361 --> 00:40:30,082
A lot of times, oh, man, it's too much trouble.

969
00:40:30,602 --> 00:40:31,882
Yeah, I was going to tell them, but I'm busy,

970
00:40:31,922 --> 00:40:33,702
and I'm just not going to do that.

971
00:40:34,203 --> 00:40:35,763
Another time, oh, man, I didn't know.

972
00:40:36,383 --> 00:40:40,604
Oh my god, you guys are building like a vector-based calculation

973
00:40:40,644 --> 00:40:40,904
system.

974
00:40:40,944 --> 00:40:41,784
I didn't know we've got one.

975
00:40:41,865 --> 00:40:42,445
It's already done.

976
00:40:42,465 --> 00:40:44,845
Oh, I could have saved you three months of work,

977
00:40:45,145 --> 00:40:47,426
but I just didn't know that you needed it.

978
00:40:48,563 --> 00:40:49,644
Another one is noise.

